section.para:
Suppose we have a composite type of the form C{T},
where T is a type and C is the context in
which it appears. Variance is a property of the context C, defined as follows:


C is covariantcovariant if S ≤ T implies that C{S} ≤ C{T}
C is contravariantcontravariant if S ≤ T implies that C{T} ≤ C{S}
C is invariantinvariant if S ≤ T does not imply any relationship between C{S} and C{T}.
